<pbcoreDescriptionDocument xmlns="http://www.pbcore.org/PBCore/PBCoreNamespace.html" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.pbcore.org/PBCore/PBCoreNamespace.html http://www.pbcore.org/xsd/pbcore-2.0.xsd"><pbcoreIdentifier source="NHPR Code">nhpr72667</pbcoreIdentifier><pbcoreIdentifier source="http://americanarchiveinventory.org">cpb-aacip/187-16pzgpxx</pbcoreIdentifier><pbcoreTitle titleType="Series">The Exchange</pbcoreTitle><pbcoreTitle titleType="Program">Higher Education Troubles   REBROADCAST</pbcoreTitle><pbcoreSubject>Public Affairs</pbcoreSubject><pbcoreDescription>After technology, housing and the automotive industry, some are predicting that the next big bubble to burst, might be higher education.  Those who suggest this point to the telltale signs: for decades, college fees have been rising faster than the American students ability to pay them. Diligence is down with students studying far less than they did fifty years ago. Also administration costs are skyrocketing, while campuses are being outfitted with multibillion-dollar dormitories and sports facilities.  Some predict that many future students could be priced out of most colleges. Others are going as far to suggest that Cambridge could become the next Detroit.  Well look at the likelihood of a college bubble and how it may be prevented.</pbcoreDescription><pbcoreGenre source="AAPB Format Genre">Call-in</pbcoreGenre><pbcoreCoverage><coverage>New Hampshire</coverage><coverageType>spatial</coverageType></pbcoreCoverage><pbcoreCreator><creator>New Hampshire Public Radio</creator><creatorRole>Producing Organization</creatorRole></pbcoreCreator><pbcoreContributor><contributor>Laura Knoy</contributor><contributorRole>Host</contributorRole></pbcoreContributor><pbcorePublisher><publisher>NHPR</publisher><publisherRole>Copyright Holder</publisherRole></pbcorePublisher><pbcoreRightsSummary><rightsSummary>2012 New Hampshire Public Radio</rightsSummary></pbcoreRigh